Its about you and me declaring our eternal undying love for each other Thats what weddings used to be about Oh no they werent Marriage for love is a relatively new phenomenon Weddings used to be about a man purchasing a woman from her father for the purpose of home management and reproduction For the upper classes it was also about combining familial assets think corporate merger Weddings were business deals with money and property changing hands A daughter was her fathers property the asking her father permission ritual originates from the practice of a man asking a father if he can buy his daughter the moneyproperty used to make that purchase is called a dowry As with any other piece of his property the father determines to whom he will sell her A wedding was simply the point of sale when property dowry and bride was exchanged hence the rituals of father walking the bride down the aisle and giving her away The vows and signing of the marriage certificate now license were oral and written contracts standard to any business transaction Such transactions always required the presence of witnesses now guests The higher ones social class the more witnesses guests as to confirmverify within the communitysocial group the status of the new woman in the family and prevent any disputes involving inheritance of wealth property and status of offspring The reception while celebratory was simply the hospitality that was custom at the time you invite people into your home you feed them Simple as that The higher the social statusclass of the womans family the bigger and more elaborate and longer the party as people would be traveling from outoftown estates etc Such hospitalityfor any social groupwas a time to impress The amount of choice a daughter had in who she would marry ie be sold to was generally determined by the surrounding culture and of the familys class The selling of ones daughter ie marrying her off to a man was often used as a means for her family to raise their financial andor social class status The entire wedding ritual is simply an acting out of the process by which a daughter was sold by her father to a man from another family Not so romantic eh

FYI wedding tax is often times not a ripoff in specific categories like DJing video production and a few other industries Weddings demand a more professional setting and in terms of the DJ it requires that you speak on the mic much more than you would need to at a standard Party gig And often times DJs who normally do partystyled gigs have to change their performance style to fit the wedding atmosphere that the clients want to have At first it may seem as though people are ripping you off but when you factor in the extra work and professionalism required to do a wedding gig you may understand the motives behind the extra costs This is just a generalization and there definitely are people out there who do take advantage of these situations but a large amount of the people providing these services especially small businesses only charge extra for legitimate reasons that may not be apparent to someone who isnt part of the wedding industry If you are someone that is worried about the price difference ask specifics as to why it costs more If they are unable to explain why there probably isnt a legit motive behind the extra costs involved Just a thought coming from a DJ that bases my prices on the situation not exterior motives

Im in agreement with others that posted about the photography should not be included in the list of rips offs I was actually planning on becoming a wedding photographer myself before I became disabled and had done a few Yes wedding photographers are expensive And theirs a reason for it Shooting a wedding vs a birthday party is two completely different things Weddings are a very formal one time event They are also the one thing you will keep from it and cherish Weddings involve alot of planning and timing The photographer essential becomes the wedding director Your also hiring a photographer based on their talent and skill Anyone can pick up a camera and push a button but not anyone can get all the shot or get them right A good photographer also spends alot of time post processing They will also come to the rehearsal and shoot A good photographer also general hires a assistant Then your talking about all the gear that is very expensive And this doesnt include all the stress that goes with it Weddings do not always go as planned and you will learn this very quickly A good photographer will have backup plans So while you may think a photographers job is basically done when heshe leaves it isnt Theirs hundreds or thousands of photos they have to go through proof and correct On top of that they all have to share the same color balance lighting and feel Thats easier said then done If a photographer messes up theirs no redues and this mistake will haunt the bride and groom for their life because they will always see the photos Catering dj band whatever while it may be a issue at the time after the wedding its not so much of a concern I seen cheep photographers work and some of it ir absolutely horrible But a true professionals work will stand out So always and I mean always hire a wedding photographer One of my friends hired their other friend to shoot their wedding photography instead of me simply because they known him much longer and he was doing photography what he called professionally I was still just establishing myself The photos turned out horrible I had to littery drive this idiot to the store to get a memory card because he neglected to bring one If his camera broke down during the wedding he would have been screwed as he had no backup And for his backup lighting needs which thank god he never used were shop lights Not only that they sure did look tacky sitting their in the church Now if they hired me I would have had a backup camera professional gear professional lighting would have been used on the formals and a assistant I also wouldnt be just slapping all the photos on a cd and having them send the photos to walmart their would have been proofs post processing and a professional lap turning them into photos maybe even a book or whatever they wanted Thats the difference from a wedding photographer vs a sports photographer doing a wedding Want to save a few bucks go with a nonwedding photographer Want quality photos get a experienced and talented wedding photographer And just because Uncle Joe or Aunt Jill has a nice dlsr and shared all kinds of vacation sunset photos with you doesnt mean they are the right choice for your wedding Listen Im not saying this to draw up business Im disabled and cant do it now But any good full time wedding photographer will have a solid schedule Thats right they get booked up fast so their no need to draw up business In fact you want to book one as far in advanced as possible I have heard many horror stories of people unable to find one because they wanted too long and they were all booked
